headline: How Steel Tariffs Will Hit the Canned Foods Aisle
summary: The Trump administration’s new 50% duty on imported steel could increase store prices for items in steel cans by 9% to 15%, according to the Consumer Brands Association, a trade group whose members include Campbell’s, Hormel Foods and Del Monte Foods.

headline: The Canned-Food Aisle Is Getting Squeezed by Rising Steel Tariffs
summary: Cans used for food require tin-coated, ultrathin sheet steel made from molten iron.  The Trump administration’s new 50% duty on imported steel could increase store prices for items in steel cans by 9% to 15%, according to the Consumer Brands Association, a trade group whose members include  Campbell’s Hormel Foods  and Del Monte Foods.  At that rate, the price of a can of vegetables costing $2 could increase by 18 cents to 30 cents.
